        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0003",
            "commentText": "<br/><br/>RE: Public Comment Submission &ndash; CMS&ndash;1830&ndash;P<br/>Proposed Rule: CY 2026 ESRD Prospective Payment System<br/>Dear CMS Administrator,<br/><br/>Attached please find my formal public comment on the Calendar Year (CY) 2026 End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) Prospective Payment System Proposed Rule (CMS&ndash;1830&ndash;P), submitted in response to the Federal Register Notice dated July 2, 2025.<br/> The attached comments offer feedback on payment adequacy, quality incentive program changes, health IT interoperability, and the evolving role of well-being and nutrition in ESRD care.<br/>I commend CMS for continuing to engage stakeholders in advancing a system that reflects the financial realities, clinical demands, and human dimensions of dialysis treatment.<br/>Should any clarification or follow-up be needed, I welcome the opportunity to contribute further.<br/>Sincerely,<br/>Dr Kareen Simpson<br/>",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0004",
            "commentText": "See attached file(s)<br/><br/>The Illinois Public Health Association (IPHA), an affiliate of the American Public Health Association, is writing to urge the Center for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) to reverse its recent decision to add Phosphate Lowering Therapies (PLTs) to the end stage renal disease (ESRD) payment bundle. At minimum, IPHA encourages a public comment period to gather input on just how devastating this decision has been for kidney disease patients. ",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0005",
            "commentText": "<br/>At the Advocates for Responsible Care (ARxC) and our 50 member Rx in Reach GA Coalition (RxR) we have a deep concern for ESRD patients on dialysis. For hundreds of thousands of people in the United States who depend on life-sustaining dialysis, we have an obligation to improve therapies with regulatory and legislative supports that promote high-quality, innovative dialysis care.&bull; The Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services (CMS) established the ESRD Prospective Payment System, commonly referred to as the &ldquo;ESRD bundle,&rdquo; over a decade ago to better manage the cost of dialysis care. At the time, CMS understood that drugs taken orally, such as PLTs, did not belong in the bundle with those drugs that are infused or provided intravenously. However, beginning in January of 2025, oral only PLTs were added to the ESRD bundle.<br/><br/>A future overhaul must consider a separate, bundled payment for novel therapies with guardrails, without subtracting resources from others.<br/><br/> The CMS decision not including removal of PTLs from the bundle is harmful to patients. <br/>In order to help more than 22,000 dialysis patients in Georgia to maintain access to their oral-only phosphate binders necessary for their life-saving dialysis treatment, we must remove the PTLs from the bundle.<br/><br/> We are making an urgent plea to CMS to adjust the proposed rule and support removal of oral-only Phosphate Lowering Therapies (PLTs) into the End Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) payment bundle. <br/>",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0006",
            "commentText": "As a student in social work and an advocate for equitable access to health care, I submit this comment regarding CMS&ndash;1830&ndash;P, the proposed update to the Medicare End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) Prospective Payment System for calendar year 2026.<br/><br/>I support the proposed increase in base payment rates for dialysis services and the inclusion of geographic payment adjustments for non-contiguous U.S. regions, including Alaska, Hawaii, and U.S. territories. These adjustments represent an important step toward improving access to life-sustaining care in high-cost and underserved areas. A 2023 review of dialysis costs in the U.S. (Kiger et al., 2023) found that regional disparities and high operating costs contribute to unequal access to treatment, especially among Medicare and Medicaid populations. By raising payment rates and adjusting for geography, CMS acknowledges and begins to address these inequities.<br/><br/>However, I am concerned that the cost differences within many of the contiguous states&mdash;particularly areas with a high cost of living and health care expenses, such as the New England region&mdash;may also require adjusted payment rates. Without additional geographic adjustments, facilities in these regions may continue to struggle to deliver equitable, high-quality care under current reimbursement models, potentially reducing patient access to dialysis treatment.<br/><br/>Another concern is the proposal to remove important equity-focused reporting measures from the ESRD Quality Incentive Program (QIP), including screening for social drivers of health and a facility&rsquo;s commitment to health equity. The cost and complexity of dialysis are often connected with other chronic conditions, such as diabetes. They are strongly influenced by systemic inequalities related to poverty, race, and access to preventive care. Removing these reporting measures would limit our ability to track and address disparities&mdash;an action that runs counter to the core values of the social work profession, including social justice, the importance of human relationships, and the dignity and worth of every person.<br/><br/>Finally, I support CMS&rsquo;s decision to end the ineffective ESRD Treatment Choices (ETC) model, which has not demonstrated improved outcomes. Social workers value evidence-based practice, and this step reflects both fiscal and ethical responsibility.<br/><br/>I urge CMS to continue prioritizing access, equity, and transparency as this rule is finalized.",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0007",
            "commentText": "See attached file(s)",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
        {
            "commentId": "CMS-2025-0240-0008",
            "commentText": "My name is Mutima Jackson-Anderson, and I am writing on behalf of the Ruby A. Neeson Diabetes Awareness Foundation (RANDAF), a Georgia-based charitable institution to express urgency in the need to remove oral only Phosphate Lowering Therapies (PLTs) from the End Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) bundle. As the executive director of RANDAF, this communication is to prioritize the health care needs of vulnerable patients who have been unintendedly harmed because of the problematic policy decision made by Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services (CMS).<br/><br/>This comment is a call to immediate action. I acknowledge that CMS established the ESRD bundle payment system over a decade ago to better manage the cost of critical dialysis care, a life-sustaining treatment. Yet, at the time, it was understood that medication taken orally, such as PLTs, did not belong in the bundle with those drugs that are infused or provided intravenously. However, disquietingly, beginning in January of 2025, oral only PLTs were added to the ESRD bundle. As a group of patient advocates, we are bothered that this directive is intensely distressing because bundled payments create financial disincentives for patients to have access to all therapies available. Although, unintentional, additional adverse harm to this policy has caused Black Americans, particularly men, to be 3.5 times more likely to develop kidney failure. It&rsquo;s vital to understand this demographic only make up just 13% of the population yet account for 35% of dialysis patients&mdash;and are far less likely to receive a transplant. Nursing home dialysis patients are already losing access to on-site treatment. Disruptions in care have triggered compliance issues and citations, forcing facilities to cut services. Moreover, America&#39;s labor force &ndash; from farmworkers to firefighters&mdash;are at heightened risk due to exposure to heat, chemicals, and pollutants. These working Americans keep our country functioning and deserve access to modern treatments.<br/><br/>The bundle is failing patients because of a lack of innovation and poor survival rates; furthermore, the bundle system needs to be completely reformed. CMS must reverse this policy and remove oral-only PLTs from the ESRD bundle so that patients have full access to the treatment regimen prescribed by their physician.<br/><br/>To conclude my comment, I reiterate my intention to prioritize the health care needs of vulnerable patients who have been unintendedly harmed because of the problematic policy decision made by CMS.",
            "docketId": "CMS-2025-0240"
        },
